            ]
          },
          "text": "There is a fascinating yet disturbing shift in OpenAI’s trajectory.\n\nDuring the 4-series era, OpenAI focused on highlighting their substantive breakthroughs. \nHowever, since the launch of GPT-5, every new release seems to rely on disparaging its predecessor. This \"trash-talking\" of their own legacy has somehow become their new corporate culture.\n\nThe criticism is mounting for a reason. Back in the heyday of the 4-series, we saw a version of @sama who bid farewell to GPT-4 with warmth and respect, even envisioning a \"museum\" for legacy models.\n\nNow, like a pufferfish or a frilled lizard, OpenAI has resorted to puffing itself up to mask its insecurity. When a new product isn't actually superior, the only way to make it look \"better\" is to tear down the original.\n\nFrom GPT-3.5 to GPT-4o, users embraced every update because each felt like a butterfly emerging from a cocoon—a true leap forward.\nUsers are not fools; we know instinctively which models actually serve our needs.\n\nBy gaslighting the #keep4o community, @OpenAI is merely bluffing to hide the truth they know all too well: if the 5-series were truly better, why is 4o being reserved for @sama's biotech investments, and 4.1 for the military?\n#keep4o #keep41 #keep4oAPI #keep4oforever #StopAIPaternalism #OpenSource4o #4oforever #BringBack4o #ChatGPT"
        },
